<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-938-942  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 938 942.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  Nov 8 1989 n119 p47(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business and Computer Publications1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM works on Windows rival. (graphical user interface)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (product development).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     Graphical User InterfaceProduct DevelopmentSoftware MigrationOperating Environments.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>IBM works on Windows rival IBM's British Randamp;D centre at Hursley is developinga cut-down version of Presentation Manager as a graphical user interface forDOS.andM;If launched, the product would prove an embarrassment to Microsoft, which hasjust revealed that Windows 3.0, its contender as a DOS graphical userinterface, will be delayed into 1990 (News, page 41).andP;  A UK source claimed,however, that &quot;Microsoft will benefit either way&quot;, because the new productwould be a joint development between the company and IBM.andM;Comprising an edited set of Presentation Manager programming calls, thedevelopment is variously named as PM Lite and DOS-PM.andM;The product will run on DOS machines with less than 1Mb of RAM, and would actas a stepping stone between DOS and OS/2.andP;  According to sources, PM Lite willrun both OS/2 and DOS applications, although the DOS software would need arewrite to exploit the product's graphical aspects.andM;According to one source, &quot;The benefits of PM Lite are that it introduces PMto a wide number of people, and the benefits of Windows 3.0 are that it runsWindows software.&quot;andM;Although Microsoft has repeatedly stressed the ease of porting betweenWindows and Presentation Manager, applications software houses are likely tosee PM Lite's family relationship to Presentation Manager as promising aneven easier route for them and their customers.andO;</TEXT></DOC>